        <h3 class="article__heading">01. Challenge</h3>

        <p>Groups Recover Together is a healthcare organization that provides medication-assisted treatment for its 6,000+ members who are struggling with opioid addiction. Their comprehensive approach to addiction treatment combines medication, group counseling, and peer support to help members on their journey to recovery. They have 80+ treatment centers across the United States, as well as a telehealth offering that I designed <a class="anchor-body" href="/case-studies/groups" target="_blank">back in 2020</a> as a Product Design contractor at thoughtbot. I joined Groups' Product Team in April 2022 as a full-time Senior Product Designer.</p>

        <p>Members (people enrolled in the Groups program) connect with all different kinds of staff members throughout their recovery journey. They meet with intake specialists, counselors, physicians, and office managers, who work together to make a member's experience seamless throughout the program. It takes a lot of hard work, coordination, and team work to do this.</p>

        <p>Members have tasks they need to complete (e.g. submit weekly drug screens and attend weekly group therapy sessions), and staff need to do everything else to keep them on track and accountable. They schedule their therapy sessions, read and record their drug screen results, follow-up on missing drug screens, engage them if their attendance drops, keep track of their expiring prescriptions ‚Äì the list goes on and on. On any given day, an office manager can have 100 tasks to complete for their member cohort (~150 members).</p>


        <h2 class="article__subheader">The Action List Email</h2>

        <p>To help keep track of these various tasks, Groups created an Action List email that was sent out every day to Staff and Counselors to help them focus on what they need to get done for the day. This email was a really great first step. It helped prevent tasks from slipping through the cracks as staff worked hard to make sure their members stayed on track.

