        <h3 class="article__heading">02. Process</h3>

        <h2 class="article__subheader">User Interviews</h2>

        <p>In order to get started, I scheduled interviews with various office managers and counselors to learn about their experience using the Action List daily email. I asked them how it fits into their workflow ‚Äì how it helps them and how it hinders them. In these preliminary conversations I try to understand the bigger picture and the context in which a tool like this exists. I look for opportunities for improvement, as well things we should keep as we move forward with a new design. These conversations were super helpful in understanding what the next steps would be design-wise, and I came away with some key things to consider:</p>

         <div class="heading-lockup">
          <div class="heading-lockup__item">
            <h5 class="heading-lockup__subheading">Insight 1</h5>
            <h4 class="heading-lockup__heading">Staff want to be able to see each others' Action Lists to make last minute coverage easier to orchestrate</h4>
          </div>

          <div class="heading-lockup__item">
            <h5 class="heading-lockup__subheading">Insight 2</h5>
            <h4 class="heading-lockup__heading">Staff want a better way to organize the tasks, whether by categorizing it themselves or applying filters to help them focus on what's important</h4>
          </div>

          <div class="heading-lockup__item">
            <h5 class="heading-lockup__subheading">Insight 3</h5>
            <h4 class="heading-lockup__heading">Staff want to be able to interact with the tasks and do things like reassign tasks, ask questions, and mark tasks as complete</h4>
          </div>
        </div>

        <h2 class="article__subheader">Design</h2>

        <p>After I had enough clarity on the context of the Action List and how it's incorporated into a staff member's daily workflow, I was ready to design what it could look like out of email and into our Digital Platform. When starting a brand new redesign like this, the first thing I do is gather inspiration from competitors and creative platforms like Dribbbl and Pinterest. In this case, I looked for UI examples of task management software, EHRs, ticketing systems, and filter experiences.</p>

        <p>After many rounds of feedback sessions with stakeholders, I landed on an interface that prioritizes simplicity over information overload. This was an interesting challenge, because every task is different and different staff roles look for different things. I identified and surfaced the common information across all the different tasks that is needed in order to evaluate and take action:</p>


